The president does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
A few days ago, he intensified the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forgets to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the Golmeda, the diploma and the cheque over ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The programme of events then includes a banquet with the President and his wife, which will be attended in addition to Norway’s King and Queen, as well as the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests.
Obama was very reluctant about the price from the beginning.
He said, for example, that he felt he wasn’t entirely worthy of the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he pointed out that this was for him "invitation to action".
