Czech discovery: a substance that also acts on ‘stealed’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that are intended to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not have as strong an effect on common virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, the patient can prolong the life of the drug and prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus propagation also results in the development of resistant viruses against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein that is responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
The metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus propagation in a different way than any drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new "improved" compounds, which were prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Deceptive and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease-induced HIV virus fission, no mature infection virus particles would arise.
When we turn off HIV protease, we also turn off the proliferation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
A little weaker but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in test tubes, also against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical designs, make the metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of Academia.
