New vaccination
Vaccines free for August children
From January onwards, children can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal infections born on August 2nd last year and later.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccine dose.
Anyone who started the vaccination already last year or earlier must also pay for further revaccination themselves.
The first dose of vaccination must be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child's life.
Last year, a quarter of families had their children vaccinated against pneumococcal disease.
The parents paid 1,600 crowns and more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest children requires four doses.
All in all, the experts estimate that the health insurances spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year on vaccine doses.
However, they save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all children’s area vaccinations.
The mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also severe infections including inflammation of the brain skin and blood poisoning.
As a result of pneumococcal infections, up to 28 children aged up to 10 years die each year after examination in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, the mandatory vaccination of children against pneumococcal disease has been introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
From January onwards, it will be paid and voluntary by the insurance companies.
That the mandatory vaccination would be better, for example, mentioned the head of the citizens' association Nahlas, Rudolf Kalovsky.
Its association is already promoting long-term pneumococcal vaccination.
The professionals at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very satisfied that we had voluntary vaccination.
This is not ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have succeeded in enforcing at least that.
“I think that’s the way we have to go now,” Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococcal disease.
At this moment we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages, doctors say.
The chairwoman of the Society of Practical Paediatricians, Hana Cabrnochova, admits that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, one could think about reducing the number of revaccinations "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary," Cabrnochova says.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to have their babies vaccinated against pneumococcal disease from next year.
The vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in that it is the first area vaccination paid by the health insurance companies and not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend the money on prevention to save them for further treatment, Cabrnochova says.
Doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
This, however, is associated with a concern of practical pediatricians, which concerns the purchase of vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines should be purchased by the insurance companies and the doctors should then receive them in the same way as other vaccines issued by the state to them.
However, some MEPs feared that the insurance companies could "extract the money from the health insurance".
Therefore, doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait for the insurance companies to pay them.
According to the estimates, the individual practical doctors will have to invest 40,000 kroner per month, which is a significant sum.
This is not going to be easy, says Cabrnochova.
