Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and Pragmatism in a Secular State.
At a time when Swiss voters voted to ban minarets and concerns about the alleged Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-thought-out report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe’s declared most secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work, "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argued study of a dispute that divided and occupied the country for one and a half decades, and its impact can still be perceived today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what the politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls “Islamic Free Spaces.”
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students about the questions they are most concerned about.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim Woman Marry a Non-Muslim Man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he claims, that make up daily life, quite contrary to the political dramas that the media employ.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arabic-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
You don’t have all the arguments on your side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists questioned by Bowen are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of purist Sunni Islam, which is associated with Saudi Arabia – who now show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism may be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
It questions the extent to which French policy makers (and the intellectual elite who are so passionate about separating church and state) really feel committed to pluralism.
