Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for almost 22 percent of reported Shanghai residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City Population and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of childbearing age must have babies “to help reduce the proportion of the aging population and alleviate the labor shortage of the future.”
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Established in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy face enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplaces.
Chinese state representatives have attributed to this policy that the critical use of natural resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to abort.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions performed, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule — including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife have been single children — and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University’s Institute of Population Research, said government officials have even recently discussed more radical changes, for example, allowing couples two children with one partner to be single children.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and swipe through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not exactly encouraging, family planning representatives said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a small rural town outside Shanghai said there was an upswing in applications from couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, urban districts did not report any change.
The municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000 still receives as an example only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of Shanghai’s Caolu community, said financial considerations are likely the main reason why many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to give their first the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and this is also legally allowed.
But they have, like many Chinese, only a small amount of government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child by the seventh month.
Yes, we are being robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the HR manager, said she wanted only one child because she was also an individual child. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone cared for us.
We’re not used to caring for others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with double careers, through which the birth rate drops, he said, it’s about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
Today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up seeing their parents struggle during the early days of China’s capitalism experiment and they don’t want a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, puts huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the room question -- "You have to renovate your apartment" -- and the life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you have to have a CV ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Develops Emissions Reduction Plan
The U.N.-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- refocused on Friday with the release of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrialized nations facing the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a definitive political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has identified both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that runs out as more than 100 top politicians from around the world arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policymakers would contribute.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has put together a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, has called “the big picture.”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which the industrialized nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave the talks a boost by promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change - from mastering floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks last week had determined.
U.S. Secretary of State for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for mandatory reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not funded by the developed nations.
This move announced that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China than the Bush administration did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging markets rising and taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough, to ensure that the cuts could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern delivered his statement an hour after Chinese Vice Secretary of State He Yafei’s statement that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked “reason” or it was “highly irresponsible” from him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China master global warming.
With the future economic direction of the great world powers at stake, break lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging countries.
The current struggle relates equally to saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the great powers were fighting to find out who should bear the costs of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have gone more aggressively to hold those countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will develop, according to Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impacts of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The alliance of small island states with 43 members submitted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the small island states’ offensive is “putting political pressure on the entire political process,” in part because they are now united and demanding action from emerging countries such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the open issues still need to be resolved before the arrival of government leaders to reach an agreement.
High-ranking officials such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s Deputy Minister disembarked from their planes and raced through the passageways of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to pin down claims to be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people come and go to the congress centre every day, guitar-playing activists hold night shows mocking countries they believe are betraying and selling, and draft contracts are hand-in-hand rather than emailed -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: Almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday there will be 60 government leaders in Copenhagen.
We are coming to the Oberliga,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
