The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa findae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-long animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa findae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body traits, Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in the journal Science on Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the relative relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassics, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Discovery confirms theories about early dino history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaurus fossils from the Triassics are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts don’t necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is often controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor and also the birds, which are known as "long-necked" lizards, the four-legged lizards belonging to the tripods and their relatives, and the plants of fres.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa findae is an original theropode.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, Nesbitt says.
On the skull of Tawa hav<0xC3><0xAD>ae, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the birds breathe more efficiently than the mammals.
In the case of Tawa findae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also possessed airbags and lightweight bones, the common ancestors of the two groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
Accordingly, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America to all parts of the world, which at that time still formed a single landmass as a supercontinent Pangea.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa findae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods speaks for itself.
The three cannot be descended from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could arise, because in South America, a lot of primitive dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare lateral line of the reptile tribe to the dominant agricultural vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still enigmatic.
During the Triassic period, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying saurians and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic era, the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while their relatives died on the border from the Triassic to the Jura.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic period and had since eaten a shadowy existence: the mammals.
