The same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality.
Dreamlikely altered waking states can occur in the most diverse forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the new-age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic rapture states, psychoses and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the brain's neural messengers - especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - derails and the interaction of different brain parts is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The connection of delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of dreaming in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 a "great similarity of being irrational to dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the inconsistencies, delusions, sensualities".
