Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis when the disposition is present.
Even hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains run hot
The crazy thing is, psychologists suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get which, says the Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether misconceptions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of viewpoint.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and illusions for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also of many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brains of healthy people hallucinate under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, Kasten says, are made up of memory contents that are usually held back.
They occur when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or underinhibited; when our brain runs hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimulation withdrawal, stress, love distress or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents said they had experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends the high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If there weren’t pictures and voices.
In the break, it can happen that a lazy boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it answers, the classmates look at it surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other misconceptions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening
Often the misconceptions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material because the teacher is introducing a new student in her eyes and ears, while explaining mathematical equations, both audible and visible to everyone else, on the board.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and far too late, she can often not distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the frats or the girl with the bloody cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her anything about it, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art from despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffering from stimulation withdrawal, they are very likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect the brain is then underworked and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was afraid of other children as a young girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at age 13 that the man she calls Dad, since she can think, is not her biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between misconceptions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is formed there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real.”
Even nocturnal dream pictures value caste as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their misconceptions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Boundary state between dream and hallucination
In our too conscious world, imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also harbors positive, creative things - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of traumatically altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams that the experiencer considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state in retrospect.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme trauma or disease-related situations, for example in polyradiculate patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self-loss and world-loss, for example, by persistent, complete incapacity for movement, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, Schmidt-Degenhard says.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intense form of foundation and meaning in a situation that is in itself unbearable, which allows us people's own ability to design, not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as a rescue of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body in the intensive care unit is condemned to motionlessness.
Claussen dives into a self-made world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lived in the early Middle Ages among nobles who made intoxicants from blood.
After being kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle into his homeland, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
It goes completely on in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is another state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories of mental journeys are still clear to me after years and in incidental details.
Clearer and more intense than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug addiction show how brittle our inner images of outer reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist summarizes Kasten, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
An experience that can also be enriching.
