75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market restricted due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what kind of profession they perform.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only half a day or do not have a permanent employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a fixed position, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
"Women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a fixed employment receive their first child, on average, only 3.7 years after the marriage, a number that rises to 4.1 years for women with a fixed employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have not realized their marriage and the first child until much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a large influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of the willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of the women during the marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the education level, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years old, depending on whether they only have primary school graduation or higher education, were on average mothers with 25.1 or 32.1 each for the first time.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with a major degree get married before their first permanent employment and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school degree do it exactly differently and first seek a permanent employment and marry after that and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
