Support for braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system back then, and as is the case now with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary braking systems in emergencies must become an obligatory feature in European cars.
In fact, they are already compulsory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the remaining vehicles a leave of absence has been set until the end of February 2011.
The action adopted by the European Union is aimed at improving the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal on the basis of the braking force carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not have to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked at full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force into the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are injured could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistance.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver reacts, the system helps him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already unavoidable, the brake assistant exerts maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
