The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its competitors.
A five-kilometre-long tunnel in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the east coast, has become the best opportunity for Acciona to establish itself in the country as a construction company and highway operator.
The city council wants to complete the construction at the end of 2014.
After the Administration has decided on Public-Private Cooperation (PPP) to advance the project according to a business plan prepared by Ernst & Young, the Administration is already in possession of a final list of candidates for construction and toll administration.
In anticipation of the offers presented in May, the estimated investments amount to 1.7 billion Australian dollars (1,047 billion euros), with three consortia, mainly consisting of European construction companies, competing with each other in the last phase.
The Transcity group is led by Acciona, the only Spanish company, and its partners are BMD and Ghella.
The first company is one of the largest construction companies in Australia, while the second, based in Italy, is one of the best specialists in civil engineering.
The Northern Direct consortium, formed by the British company Laing O'Rourke, the Australian Transfield, responsible for infrastructure and the French Bouygues group, is competing against the Acciona team.
The third and final consortium, which is in the shortlist, is called LBRJV, formed from the capital of the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German construction company Hochtief, which in turn belongs to ACS), the local Baulderstone (owned by the German Bilfinger Berger Group) and the French company Razel, which specializes in public construction.
The Australian infrastructure market promises enormous construction and privatization, but has a hurdle to overcome, since you can only get access by buying a local construction company.
A strategy followed by the aforementioned companies Hochtief or Bilfinger, in addition to Asian references, and which has yet to be pursued by the Spanish construction giants.
Even ACS has gained access to this market only through its 30% stake in Hochtief, the owner of the Leighton.
Millions of assets
Acciona focuses on this geographical area of utmost importance for the industry, where it is already well known for its activity as an energy supplier and in the desalination industry.
It already has its largest windmill park (192 MW) in Victoria and leads the group of companies tasked with building and managing the Adelaide desalination plant with a budget of 700 million.
His intention is now to consolidate in these two areas and use these synergies to gain access to the construction and infrastructure branches.
The subterranean toll line, promoted by the City of Brisbane's Office of Infrastructure and named Northern Link (Northern Towong) has the purpose of connecting the western Toowong highway with the Kelvin Grove bypass (see map) over a length of 5 kilometres through Brisbane tunnels, the largest of which is the road to the dam.
The timetable issued by the city administration provides for the award for summer 2010 and the start of construction work in December next year.
Even if this toll line is to open for traffic in the last months of 2014, it is expected that the construction work will continue until 2016.
The tunnel was designed in 2005.
It has two lanes in each direction, an electronic toll system and a complex ventilation system.
