CNMV approves the public exclusion tender of Paternina submitted by investment company Mer
The National Stock Exchange Commission (CNMV) approved the public exclusion tender for Federico Paternina submitted by investment company Mer on October 9.
The supervisory authority stated that it had approved this invitation to tender after it had been demonstrated that the conditions were in accordance with the legally binding laws and that the content of the explanatory memorandum submitted could therefore be considered "sufficient" according to the amendments made last December 2.
CNMV has also announced that this offer is aimed at the acquisition of 550,008 shares of Federico Paternina at a price of EUR 7.65 per share, which in turn constitutes 8.95% of the share capital, consisting of EUR 6,142,786 in shares registered on the Madrid and Bilbao stock exchanges.
In addition, it was announced that 5,592,778 million shares have been fixed, which cannot be transferred in any way until the closing of the tender and the price of which has been fixed by Federico Paternina in accordance with the legally binding laws.
New Vehicle Assessment Programs
In these days of storms and accidents not only the car workshops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are transported to the workshops, where an appraiser must assess the damage and repair costs.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including the parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes
That’s why almost 100% of appraisers use these types of systems.
Accident assessment and repair service and application providers collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process it thereafter and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American Solera Group, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are produced with their products.
The two other companies competing in the tool market for review and reporting are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Audatex’s sales manager, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each providing the information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is getting bigger and bigger, to the point that more versions, variants and engines have come to the market in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, work begins for the companies.
It is a tedious task, because every single one of the one thousand vehicle parts has to be catagolicized and its price entered.
In addition, a "smart" graphic image is created from each model, on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If it is a much-selling model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information for 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
More than 99% of the vehicle fleet on the roads.
For the purpose of carrying out documentation work and creating databases, Audatex has eight centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests EUR 90 million annually in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers get the updates every other day.
The elaboration of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways, thus offering different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the partial or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide to inform about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
By looking through the products that Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products being AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint prices.
This tool is paid for depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each report.
The most expensive will be for customers who rarely use it, at most ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, any insurance company that produces thousands of reports negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can completely identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly line only by means of the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is an online service open to the specialist market that can be used for vehicles that have been declared a total damage.
Their statistics service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses, or obtaining information about brand and model deviations.
It can be used, for example, to examine how many models of a particular car brand had to go to the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident during a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among other things, Gt Estimates, which is also intended for appraisers and provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns or maintenance of vehicles.
The GT-Guide for Opinions is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 appraisers and 53 insurance companies.
Its business volume has increased by 20% annually over the last three years and sales in 2008 amounted to EUR 10.8 million.
At the beginning of last year, they also started to go on the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its business is done in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America, working with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
Solera Group’s total worldwide sales (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounted to $557 million, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
